<h2 id="key-principles-for-ai-in-humanistic-research">Key principles for AI in humanistic research</h2>

<h3 id="1-ai-is-a-thinking-partner-not-an-authority">1. AI is a thinking partner, not an authority</h3>
<p>LLMs generate plausible-sounding text. They don’t “know” things the way a scholar does. Treat AI output as a draft to be interrogated, not a finding to be cited.</p>

<h3 id="2-verify-everything-against-primary-sources">2. Verify everything against primary sources</h3>
<p>AI models can and do fabricate citations, misrepresent arguments, and get facts wrong (often called “hallucination”). Any factual claim that comes from an AI should be verified before it enters your work.</p>

<h3 id="3-transparency-matters">3. Transparency matters</h3>
<p>If you used AI tools in your research, say so. Many journals and institutions are developing policies on AI disclosure. Even where policies don’t yet exist, intellectual honesty calls for transparency.</p>

<h3 id="4-consider-the-epistemological-implications">4. Consider the epistemological implications</h3>
<p>Humanities research often values close reading, interpretive nuance, and positionality. AI tools can shortcut some of these processes in ways that may undermine the kind of knowledge you’re trying to produce. Ask: <em>does this tool help me think more carefully, or does it replace the thinking I should be doing?</em></p>

<h3 id="5-know-your-institutions-policies">5. Know your institution’s policies</h3>
<p>Your university, department, and individual instructors or advisors may have specific guidelines about AI use in coursework, qualifying exams, and dissertations. Know the rules that apply to you.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="practical-starting-points">Practical starting points</h2>

<p>If you want to experiment with AI in your research, here are some lower-risk entry points:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Brainstorming and outlining:</strong> Use AI to generate alternative framings of your argument or to suggest counterarguments. You’re still doing the thinking — the AI is just prompting you.</li>
  <li><strong>Plain-language summaries:</strong> Ask an AI to explain a methodological concept in simpler terms, then verify the explanation against the source text.</li>
  <li><strong>Translation assistance:</strong> If you work with sources in multiple languages, AI can provide rough translations for triage purposes. Always have a qualified reader check anything you cite.</li>
  <li><strong>Writing feedback:</strong> Paste in a draft paragraph and ask for feedback on clarity, structure, or tone. This is closer to using a writing tutor than to having the AI write for you.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="what-ai-should-not-replace">What AI should NOT replace</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Archival research.</strong> AI cannot visit archives, read handwriting in context, or understand the materiality of sources.</li>
  <li><strong>Close reading.</strong> AI can summarize a text, but it cannot perform the kind of sustained, interpretive engagement that humanistic scholarship requires.</li>
  <li><strong>Ethical judgment.</strong> Decisions about how to represent communities, handle sensitive material, or navigate power dynamics in research require human judgment.</li>
  <li><strong>Citation and attribution.</strong> Never cite a source you haven’t read yourself, even if an AI told you about it.</li>
</ul>

